AB  - Ceftazidime is a 3rd generation cephalosporin active against Pseudomonas
      aeruginosa. Avibactam is an inhibitor of class A, C and some class D
      β-lactamases. The antibacterial spectrum of ceftazidime-avibactam covers
      95% of P. aeruginosa isolates and >99% of enterobacteria, including
      strains carrying extended-spectrum β-lactamases (ESBLs). Selection of
      resistant mutants in Klebsiella pneumoniae and Enterobacter cloacae
      strains producing KPC-3 or KPC-2 after exposure to ceftazidime-avibactam
      has been described by the appearance of one or more amino acid changes in
      the Ω-loop of the β-lactamase. These strains usually regain susceptibility
      to meropenem. There is evidence of a shorter multidrug-resistant organisms
