      replaces alanine (T263A). The CZA-resistant strain showed the capsular
      locus KL3 and antigen locus O1v2. Other important virulence factors were
      identified: fimbrial adhesins type 1 and type 3, as well as the cluster of
      iron uptake systems aerobactin, enterobactin, salmochelin, and
      yersiniabactin included in integrative conjugative element 10 (ICEKp10)
      with the genotoxin colibactin cluster. Herein, we report the molecular
      characterization of the first hypervirulent CZA-resistant ST13
      KPC-70-producing K. pneumoniae strain in Portugal. The emergence of
      CZA-resistant strains might pose a serious threat to public health and
      suggests an urgent need for enhanced clinical awareness and epidemiologic
      surveillance.
