AB  - BACKGROUND: The production of carbapenem-hydrolyzing β-lactamases is one
      of the most concerning resistance mechanisms since it eliminates the last
      therapeutic option against multidrug resistant microorganisms. AIM: To
      determine the production of KPC and NDM-1 type carbapenemases, using
      phenotypic and genotypic methods, in isolated enterobacteria in a clinical
      laboratory in the city of Maracay, Venezuela. METHODS: The production of
      carbapenemases was determined by phenotypic (according to the Malbrán
      algorithm) and genotypic methods (amplification of the blaNDM-1 and blaKPC
      genes by PCR) in clinical isolates of Enterobacteriaceae during the period
      March-August 2018. RESULTS: 605 Enterobacteriaceae of different species
      were identified, being Escherichia coli the strain with the highest
      percentage of isolation (61.3%), followed by Klebsiella pneumoniae
      (14.9%). Sixteen strains (2.64%) were positive for carbapenemases
      production: 13 strains of K. pneumoniae and three of the Enterobacter
      cloacae complex. PCR showed that 14 strains (87.5%) carry the blaNDM-1
      gene and two strains (12.5%) the blaKPC gene; 100% agreement was observed
      between phenotypic determination and PCR for both groups of enzymes.
      CONCLUSIONS: The results of this study showed a higher incidence of
      metallo-β-lactamase type NDM-1, which rapid dissemination and consequently
      difficult control has been cause of epidemiological alert. The
      identification of the type of enzyme would allow establishing more
      accurate management and control strategies in order to eradicate these
      pathogens.
